@node prolo " Prologue"

   This guide treats of the coins of Spain from  the Greek epoch up to
Euro in a revision to the different coins minted by the different ones
peoples and cultures that have existed in the history of Spain and its
passenger existence like the 134 years of life of the peseta.

   The format that I have chosen to been the guide for its versatility
its easy one  handle  and for being  functional in  all the  models of
Amiga,  in fact this  guide it has  been  elaborated in one Amiga 500;
another  motive is that the  images of the coins are difficult to find
and have right of image, but this small obstacle is seen rewarded with
more information of which it can to offer a  normal book,  since it is
the  dictionary  of terms  and a  selection  of  sayings  and  popular
sayings.

    I hope that you it is useful specially to that estais beginning in
world of the numismatics.

@endnode

@node primer " The First coins"

   The first  Spanish coins were minted imitating the coins greeks and
fenicians,  this way we have  coins of  identical  appearance to these
cultures which are but mint in the zone of the east where extended its
influence  for  the  colonies  and  factories  that  these  they  were
possessing in those distant times.

   @{" Dracma " link dracm}

   Also we have the  genuinely  Iberian coins  minted with  figures of
warriors or warriors astride,  generally armed with lance; minted with
materials as the bronze or the silver,  these coins venian accompanied
of two texts the place of coinage and of the tribe or populate minted,
this way as is believed the second text that always finishes in "sken"
it comes to mean that it belongs or is ownership or use of for example
in the  text "Unicesken"  comes to mean  currency of  the indigeto; or
"Ausken" coins of the ausones.
   An example of  currency would be the  Quadrans of Cessation, or the
Iberian Denario of Icalgusken this  already minted in the times of the
Roman invasion and his influence.

@endnode

@node dracm " Dracma"

   Greek coin of silver,  which had its use  also between  the Romans,
almost equivalent to @{"denario" link dena}, it was equivalent to four sesterces.

   In Spain was  minted the  Iberian  dracma in  Iltirta,  Sagunto and
Saitabi coins.

@endnode

