@node asa " AS-ACE"

   Primitive Roman  currency fused in  bronze and of changeable weight
until that of a  pound was fixed.  Later the coin  and it lessened the
weight, but preserving its value of 12 ounces.

@endnode
@node blan " BLANCA-WHITE"

   Coin ancient of @{"fleece" link diccio}, according  to the  times it had  different
value and lately that of half copper maravedi.

@endnode
@node caste " CASTELLANO-CASTILIAN"

   Castilian  coin of gold  of the  Middle Ages  which value  would be
equivalent to 10 current pesetas.

@endnode
@node centa " CENTAVO-CENT"

   American's  and  Philippine's  coin,  minted  in bronze,  copper or
nickel, which costs one cent of weight.
   Cents  were minted  during  the colonial Spanish epoch  in Cuba and
Puerto Rico and  The Philippines,  though in the peninsula other coins
were minted as maravedi coin or the peseta.

@endnode
@node corna " CORNADO"

   The name comes given from crown.

   Ancient  coin of  copper  with a  fourth part of silver,  which had
recorded a wreath,  it circulated in  times of  the king  Sancho IV of
Castile and of his successors up to the Catolic Kings.

   The more ancient were equivalent to 1 quarter and 1 maravedi and to
less of half of the modern maravedis of the century XIX.

@endnode
@node coro " CORONA-CROWN"

   Ancient coin of gold,  which had a wreath engraved  and it ran from
reign of Juan II of Castile,  up to ends of the century XVIII.  It had
diverse values  in times  of the  Catolic Kings it  was equivalent  to
approximately 11 royals of silver.

   Coin of silver  of very low law,  which gave the orders to work the
king Enrique II of Castile.

@endnode
@node cuar " CUARTO-QUARTER"

   Coin of  copper of the  ancient  system,  which  value  belong to 4
maravedis of @{"fleece" link diccio}, or 3 cents of peseta.

@endnode
@node cruza " CRUZADO-CRUSADER"

   Ancient  coin of Castile,  with a  cross in the obverse,  that with
silver of low law give the orders of  minted Enrique II, giving it the
value of one maravedi of silver, but that prompt reduce the third part
in conformity with its real value.

   Ancient currency of Castile of @{"fleece" link diccio}, that order minted Enrique II
giving it the value of the seventh one of royal of silver.
Though in the  print of the currency  did not exist any cross, it took
the name to imitation of them of silver minted in the same epoch.

@endnode
@node dena " DENARIO"

   Roman coin of silver, equivalent to ten aces or four sesterces.

   Roman coin of gold, which was worth hundred sesterces.

@endnode
@node dina " DINAR"

   Arabic coin of gold which it minted from the end of the century VII
and whose weight was of near to 4 grs.
Is necessary to  remember  that it is the currency  that circulated in
the Moslem Spain.

@endnode
@node dine " DINERO-MONEY"

   Coin of silver and  copper used in  Castile in the  century XIV and
that was equivalent to two cornados.

   Money of Burgos: Golden coin  of very  low law  ordered  to work in
Burgos for the king Alfonso X, value two @{"pepiones" link pepi}.

@endnode
@node doba " DOBLA"

   Castilian coin of gold,  minted in the  Middle Ages, of law, weight
and value changeable.

   Dobla the band: Golden coin minted  in times of Juan II and Enrique
IV, with the shield of @{" Order of the Band " link diccio} in the obverse.

@endnode
@node doblo " DOBLON-DOUBLOON"

   Coin ancient of gold, with different value according to the epochs,
up to the middle of the century XVII it came to fix to 4 @{"duros" link dur}.
   Was called  for of  the   people,  from the  Catholic  Kings to the
excellent major that had the weight of 2 castilian or doblas.

   Doubloon of to hundred: Coin  ancient of gold,  of the weight of 50
doubloons that value 100 you turn of gold.

   Doubloon of to four: Coin ancient of gold, which was worth 4 doblas
of gold.

   Doubloon of to eight: Coin  ancient  of  gold,  which  was  worth 8
shields or an ounce of gold.

   Simple doubloon: Imaginary coin of value of 60 royals.

@endnode

@node duca " DUCADO-DUCHY"

   Golden coin that use up to ends of the century XVI which changeable
value, it managed to be of approximately 7 pesetas.

   Imaginary equivalent  coin to 11 royal  of @{"fleece" link diccio}, increased in one
half more for the law of February  1860 and return  after to its first
value.

@endnode
@node dur " DURO"

   Coin of silver that was worth 5 pesetas.

   Coin of another metal that is equivalent to 5 pesetas.

@endnode

