@node rea "REAL-ROYAL"

   Coin of silver, of the value of 34 maravedis equivalent to 25 cents
of peseta.

   Royal of to fifty: Coin ancient of silver,  of the weight and value
of 50 royals of double silver.

   Royal of to four: Coin of silver,  of the value of  the half of the
royal one of to eight.

   Royal of to two: Coin of silver,  of the value  of the half  of the
royal one of to four.

   Royal of to eight: Coin  ancient of silver,  which was worth  eight
royals of old silver.

   Royal of farthing: Coin  ancient of Catalonia,  which was worth two
sueldos.

   Royal of silver: Effective  coin  of  silver  which  had  different
values, the more current was of two royal of fleece, or 68 maravedis.

   Royal of double silver  or of old silver: Coin  of  change  of  the
value of  16 quarters.  32 royal of  this currency  were composing the
doubloon of change, that it was of 68 royal and 8 maravedis of fleece.

   Royal fort: Coin  worked in Mexico  and that circulated  in America
with value of two royal and way of fleece.

   Royal Valencian: Coin that circulated in Valencia in century XVIII,
with value of 12 quarters and 3 maravedis of fleece of Castile.

@endnode
@node seste " SESTERCIO-SESTERCE"

   Coin of Roman, equivalent silver to ten aces or four sesterces.

   Roman coin of gold, which was worth hundred sesterces.

@endnode
@node soli " SOLIDO-OCCURRED"

   Or solidus: Roman coin of gold that was worth 25 denarios of gold.

@endnode
@node suel " SUELDO"

   Sueldo or Burgales: Ancient  coin  of  Castile  that  was  worth 12
dineros of to 4 meajas, or 23 cents of peseta.

@endnode
@node diccio " Dictionary of terms"

   Here the terms related come gathered with  the coins, already it is
for its form of coinage, materials  or uses and  customs of the alloys
according to the epochs.

   - Alloy: Solid blend of a  metal with other  one or others produced
     for merger combines or agglutination, the object is to change the
     properties of the metals it bases, to increase others as sheen or
     mechanical hardness.

   - Almoravide or almoarabe: Moslem  reationaries of  nomadic African
     origin converted to the Islam that they ocuppied the power of the
     Moslem Spain, when they came in their help.

   - Obverse:  Face  of  a   currency  or  medal  that  is  considered
     principally for to take the bust of a person or another motive.

   - Mint: Place where currency is coined. To the persons in charge of
     coining them  coins it calls the  person in charge  purses and of
     these Teacher Purse.

   - Cent: Real or imaginary coin that is  worth the hundredth part of
     it monetary unit, it is royal, peseta, shield or weight.

   - Milling (or contour): It is the  singing of the  currency and can
     be engraved or not.  It started realizing in the century XVIII to
     prevent one fraudulent activity the "sheared one called" that was
     consisting of smoothing the contour or the edges to obtain golden
     powder or silver.

   - FNMT: Initials of the National Factory of Coin and Stamp.

   - Liga: Quantity  of copper that  is mixed  with the  gold and  the
     silver when it coins currency.

   - Mark: Weight of  average frees or 230 grs.  for gold  and silver,
     divided  in gold: 50 Castilians,  silver: 8 ounces;  according to
     value of the century XI to the XII.

   - Metical: Name  of the most  former  unit of  the system  monetary
     Arabic, equivalent to 4,4 grs.

   - Cut coin: The coin  that does  not have milling,  not even adorn,
     not legend in the singing.

   - Imaginary coin: The coin  that has not existed  or does not exist
     already and nevertheless it is used as account unit for contracts
     and changes; like duchy of silver or the pound or the ECU.

   - Coin jaquesa: The coined  one for the  kings of Aragon,  first in
     Jaca and later in other cities of that kingdom, with mold, weight
     and law always determined.

   - Coin "obsidional": The special  coin  that is  coined  in a  town
     besiege.

   - Coin  of "soplillo":  That  of  copper,  of  short  value,  which
     circulated in Spain during the reigns of Felipe IV and Carlos II.

   - Coin "trabucante": The  one that has  slightly  more of the legal
     weight.

   - Coin  of fleece:  The  coined  one  with  league,  in  changeable
     proportions,  of  silver  and  copper  and  only  of copper  from
     Felipe's V reign.

   - Ounce: Weight that is equivalent to 28,7 grs.
     It is one of 16 equal  parts of the weight of the pound  and that
     of the frame of silver it is divided in 8 ochavos.
     Twelfth part of the ace or the Roman pound.

   - Order of the Band: Order of cavalry founded on Spain for the king
     Alfonso XI of  Castile for the years of 1330 and whose particular
     emblem it was a red  band or cochineal  powder of four fingers of
     width,  which they  were bringing  the gentlemen  on the straight
     shoulder,  from where it was crossing  for back and  chest to the
     left side.

   - Back: In coins and medals, part opposite to the obverse.

   - Fleece: League of  silver and copper  with which ancient currency
     was worked.

@endnode

@node anec " Anecdotes and curiosities"
   During  the reign  of  Alfonso XII and  Amadeo I of Savoy they were
coined coins of 5 pesetas or since call it popularly like "duro".
    So was called Amadeo to  the coin of 5 pesetas coined in silver of
high quality  coined in 1867  during  the  reign  of Amadeo I of Savoy
until 1873.   Besides was coined gold  coins of 25 and 100 pesetas but
like him reign only during two years, was coned 150 pieces, been these
coins of high value for the collectors.
    Today in day they are bandaged  these in street markets and tracks
but you  are all there  and  have care  because  there are  false five
peseta coins,  being obvious for color,  the weight and the sound, the
five peseta coin  truthful is of silver and the false coins are of tin
or pewter and do not have the same color weight and sound.

    During the Spanish civil war in  republican government,  due to it
metal lack for the  warlike effort,  was seen obliged to made coins of
paper,  the above  mentioned coins  are a carton to circulate with the
official stamp of  the  government in  the back  and in the  obverse a
stamp  of  post  office  that  equivalent  to  value of  the  supposed
currency.   Apart from it coinage  of official form of  coins for  the
government of the republic,  it was practical very common the one that
different  regions and villages,  were coining  its own coins,  giving
origin to a variety of coins in all kinds of metals, brass, zinc.

    During Franco's government was minted a coin of silver,  for value
of 100 pesetas,  curiously this ostentation  to extract a currency for
this value in 1966,  without a  support since  former it was happening
with the silver American, did that this coin was worth more the silver
with which it was coined that for the value of 100 pesetas that it was
representing, this was it causes of its prompt retreat of the traffic.
This to originated that today in day it  FNMT coins coins of silver of
2000 pesetas, the FNMT recovers in health due to that in this case the
true value of the silver that it uses does  not come not to the fourth
one part of the facial value with which it records us.

    The ECU has  the honor of  being the currency  with the most short
life, in world of the coins,  in fact has not managed  to circulate as
official currency, but if as currency of collection,  already it is in
silver like in gold.

    Another way of forging  coins is by means  of the "achocolamiento"
like it  happens with the  American coins of  half a dollar  of silver
with  the  bust  of  Kennedy  that  they  seem  of silver  but if  you
concentrate on the singing is seen that inside it is of copper, though
this is also a habitual practice for them issuing  entities especially
with commemorative  coins, though  they have that  to specify  of that
material they have been coined and bathed.

    The popularly known  one as Rubia(Blonde) the Spanish peseta, in a
beginning born in silver, and the last peseta of silver was the peseta
of 1933, for in 1944 to happen to be the blonde coined in copper up to
coming 1982 and to fall down in most down its history  to be coined in
aluminium, we remember that in 1937 during the civil war was coined in
brass.  But always of a size  respectable up to 1989  when it  to be a
button,  also it is that  to remember  that in its glorious  stage the
coins of  peseta of values facial high  places managed to be coined in
golden alloy  of 900 thousandth,  coins of 10, 20, 25  and 100 pesetas
from 1870  until 1904  with them 20 pesetas of  Alfonso XIII and it is
that the loss of the colonies affect to the quality of the coinages.

    The Spanish coins of  the same facial value and the same year even
that they look like all equal they are different, or the flower of lys
of the singing this appearing towards the obverse or towards the back,
other one marks that them  it differentiates are the stars that appear
in the back,  which it indicates  us it date of its real coinage, this
way coins exist  that in the obverse  they have a date in concrete but
they have  been coined in the  successive years  and it does that some
coins cost more than different, because even being with a date in make
concrete,  the date of coinage is  different and it  has could to be a
limited issue, making increase its value.

    The coins with fault of  factory they are in  the habit of quoting
more than the  normal ones without fault,  for those people  that they
like the different and only thing.

    The paper  coins begins  to circulate  officially in  Spain during
Alfonso's XII reign although  already exist bills or I.O.U.s that were
circulating in the middle of  the century XIX, as curiosity until 1937
during it civil war the first genuinely Spanish bills were not stamped
till then imprimian in England more concretly for:
 Bradbury, Wilkinson and Cia. in New Malden, Surrey

